title: For Sale:  Samson Evolution Handguard Rail 7"
postcontent:
7" Samson Handguard with thermal bushings to ttach to standard barrel nut.  Easy swap and highly configurable handguard.  This is a brand new takeoff in perfect condition.  Features•6010 T6 Aluminum Construction•Mil-Spec Hard Coat Anodized Finish•Uses Factory Barrel Nut (not included)•303 Stainless Thermal bushing Reduces Heat Transfer•Mil-Spec Picatinny Continuous Top Rail with Dual Alignment Tabs•1.8" Outer Diameter (Facetted)•1.56" Inner Diameter (Fits Most Suppressors)•No Specialized Tools Required For Installation
 
 
 
The Samson Manufacturing Evolution Series free float rails are customizable AR-15 handguards. The Evo rail attaches to a standard barrel nut with a two piece thermal bushing constructed of stainless steel, two locking tabs ensure the rail does not rotate under stress. The thermal bushing along with the generous ventilation slots help to keep heat from transferring into the handguard and into the operator's hand. The continuous top rail allows you to mount optics anywhere along the top of the rifle and allows same-plane iron sights to be mounted.  The interior of the tube is 1.56" in diameter, allowing most suppressors to fit underneath.
 
Installation of the Evolution series handguards does not require special tools. Since the standard barrel nut (not included) is used to mount the handguard only the delta ring, weld spring and snap ring must be removed. This means you can install the EVO rail system without removing the barrel from the upper receiver, a step that requires specialized tools such as receiver blocks, barrel nut wrench or AR-15 multi-tool. The delta ring must be cut if you do not remove the barrel from the upper.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Zastava M83 .357 Mag
postcontent: I bought this a few years back from Cabela's. It was made in '92 in Yugoslavia and, supposedly, they were used as PD service pistols for a while.It's a double/single action .357 and pretty much a direct copy of a Smith & Wesson model 27. It's a 6 shot with a 4-1/2" barrel all blued.The gun is in perfect shape, bluing is 100 %, it's never had any issues.  I have had to make a few tools to work on it, like a jig for putting in the main spring and a split flathead screwdriver. It's just too big for me to carry concealed and too small to deer hunt with, so I'm looking for something else.It'll come with a speed loader and a box of .357 Hornady JHPs and the "tools" that I made for it.  And a nylon shoulder holster if you'd like it.  I might also have some .38 special JHPs depending on how the weather is this weekend.Yes, I listed this under S&W for the manufacturer.  They don't have Zastava and I wanted something.And, just because I know that you're going to look it up, here's the history: Zastava produced these in the early 90's, this one was 1992.  Most of them went to the Serbian military during the split of Yugoslavia.  The batch that came to the US was used as a service pistol, but I can't find out by whom.  Since that's the case, the trigger is what you'd expect from a service pistol--stiff.  I've never had any problems with it, but some folks online have.  If you have a tendency to PULL a trigger instead of SQUEEZE it, you're going to have trouble.
